Y_4hBJ74UNgQPVCvJinpbFlDaL55DR-PiRs5c6L1LboX_shdwbAPqcH5qnW4N6rF5K5i9KgHfwG=
7niNNv3Zl7slCvfwt3kwZgm-AnA4ubRR5pi11aphHG1rN_SMkIgMqsPGq8bD307MJSVV26ssFAE=
MIZv4BpxC2UnVwGacbzAP_WiLTsubqZK6Bbi29QDQcejK4-J9eIA5YiXKMc96Cf-43b9gegwXSM=
ZCi92LhAG5smb4NXOMEn78_wyEz8HGR4Ct1Kklv61owGNXejcUyEI8bR7_GKizfUxivHgRPi4Fv=
UtQMW-hknvQZJhIXPHED1ylng ) , and it has to do with the conclusion about fr=
iction. I wrote towards the end:

Set aside the dramatic centuries-spanning exposition; the fundamental point=
 is that the removal of friction leads to a different set of trade-offs. In=
 the case of targeting and tracking, the payoff is a massive increase in co=
nsumer welfare by virtue of access to all of the world=E2=80=99s informatio=
n (Google), and all of the world=E2=80=99s people (Meta); in the case of th=
ings like dark patterns and personal appeals, the payoff is ordering sungla=
sses for your upcoming fishing trip at 10am and having them in hand at 4pm,=
 or, more broadly, to have access to anything you need no matter where you =
live.

To note these trade-offs is not to say that the trade-off is worth it or no=
t; it=E2=80=99s to note that the trade-offs exist. And, to that end, the fr=
ustration so many feel about the FTC=E2=80=99s recent actions, particularly=
 this specific lawsuit, is the extent to which the Commission seems determi=
ned to act as if trade-offs don=E2=80=99t exist.

Running a successful business =E2=80=94 i.e. making money =E2=80=94 depends=
 on there being some sort of scarcity; that scarcity is not always a natura=
l one. An example I often use to make this point is Stratechery: the cost f=
or me to serve one additional customer is effectively zero; I pay to develo=
p software that, from a certain way of looking at things, makes the experie=
nce of consuming my content worse (i.e. you have to pay, sign-in, etc.). Yo=
u could certainly pirate my content or hack my paywall, but that=E2=80=99s =
kind of a big pain in the rear end and/or unethical: I=E2=80=99m selling bo=
th convenience of access and also my ongoing thinking and writing and podca=
sting as a service =E2=80=94 I trust that you find it worthwhile to pay bec=
ause you want me to continue doing what I=E2=80=99m doing.

Another example is music streaming: what the music labels are now selling v=
ia Spotify and Apple Music and whoever else will take their terms is not mu=
sic; both the distribution of a single music file and the cost of serving o=
ne additional customer is effectively zero, which is why piracy scales so n=
icely (indeed, given its peer-to-peer nature piracy is arguably the best sc=
aling distribution channel). Rather, Spotify is convenient : for one low mo=
nthly rate you get access to nearly all of recorded music, on basically any=
 device with Internet connectivity.

Google and Meta, meanwhile, take this to an even more extreme level, by bei=
ng free to end users; the scarce resource they are harvesting is attention,=
 which they monetize via advertising. This also has the benefit of maximizi=
ng leverage on their massive fixed costs: being free means those expensive =
data centers and fiber links are being used constantly, which is fine becau=
se more usage means more opportunities for advertising, which itself scales=
 via self-serve ad models.

This last point is an important one: it is usually better to monetize a fix=
ed cost resource with ongoing revenue, which is generally achieved by provi=
ding an ongoing service. The alternative is something like a foundry: TSMC =
invests billions of dollars in a new fab, and makes that money back by sell=
ing individual chips; the costs of those chips are generally not the raw ma=
terials (which are on the order of cents or tens of cents per chip, dependi=
ng on chip size), but rather the cost of the fab itself.

That=E2=80=99s an extreme example, but an interesting comparison point for =
Amazon: for many years now Amazon 3rd-merchant sales have been the biggest =
part of Amazon.com; in that model Amazon charges merchants to hold their in=
ventory and a percentage of sales. Amazon=E2=80=99s costs are the warehouse=
 space and fulfillment. Fulfillment entails having a picker and delivery dr=
iver, which are marginal costs, while the warehouse space, robotics, etc, i=
s a fixed cost; to be clear, this is overly simplistic, particularly in ter=
ms of the opportunity cost of the warehouse, robotic capacity, etc.

What is obvious, though, is that Amazon wants more and more of its logistic=
al capacity to be leverage-able fixed costs, not marginal costs. And, by th=
e same token, it seems obvious that Amazon should desire that those costs b=
e covered by recurring revenue =E2=80=94 i.e. Amazon wants to cover its fix=
ed costs with subscriptions while only charging the marginal unit cost for =
whatever good it delivers. And, as I noted yesterday, the cleanest way to a=
ccomplish this is to simply require Prime for all Amazon.com customers (i.e=
. the Costco model); that, though, ultimately reduces scale by limiting Ama=
zon=E2=80=99s addressable market. Instead Amazon is arguably trying to have=
 its cake and eat it too by imposing dark patterns on those who don=E2=80=
=99t want to pay up.

Let=E2=80=99s be clear: there=E2=80=99s a lot about Amazon I don=E2=80=99t =
like, including all of the ads, the knock-off products, the fake reviews, e=
tc. All of these issues, though, are a function of an entity that is optimi=
zing for scale at the expense of marginal costs. Scale means selling more t=
hings, which means optimizing for more selection and lower prices, which me=
ans preferring ways of making money =E2=80=94 like ads and subscriptions =
=E2=80=94 that get better with scale, over things like unit margins that ac=
tually reduce sales (by raising prices).

It=E2=80=99s this scale, though, that makes things like same day delivery v=
iable, and it=E2=80=99s that scale and capability that is the scarce resour=
ce Amazon is ultimately seeking to make its money on. No one else has the l=
ogistical capabilities Amazon does =E2=80=94 just ask Shopify ( https://str=
atechery.com/2023/shopify-exits-logistics-the-shopify-logistics-side-quest-=
whither-buy-with-prime/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0=
