LdZ61ln0TZ9uJWtCfZfXTJw2DOtVIPklEPqxJa8Ha6jgKEBSrF4AXb6-v6BnAARdAlsqC9VXat8=
hQQpVQlzn7OnHaiIQ ) last month, and Microsoft=E2=80=99s announcement of Fab=
ric with CoPilot capabilities built in. It seems apparent =E2=80=94 and fra=
nkly, makes intuitive sense =E2=80=94 that the data storage providers see p=
roviding LLM capabilities as table stakes. At the same time, it also reinfo=
rces the idea that it=E2=80=99s not apparent that LLM capabilities will in-=
and-of-themselves be a long-term differentiator, or moat; what is a moat, t=
hough, is holding a company=E2=80=99s data =E2=80=94 storage is sticky, whi=
ch is to say that LLMs may attract customers, but inertia and egress costs =
will keep them.

Neeva/Snowflake and MosaicML/Databricks also seem like the right pairing: S=
nowflake abstracts everything away from customers in Snowflake managed stor=
age with a Snowflake proprietary schema, and it makes sense to add on a nat=
ural language interface on top of that (even if that interface is powered b=
y an open source LLM, or OpenAI). Databricks, meanwhile, has an open source=
 heritage (Apache Spark), and more of a picks-and-shovels approach; this ve=
ry much fits with MosaicML which offers both open source models and tools f=
or training data (Databricks is also much stronger in terms of storing data=
 for machine learning).

MosaicML and Databricks also solve specific problems for the other. MosaicM=
L is, by all accounts, doing quite well, and growing rapidly; the key now w=
ill be in building out a salesforce and figuring out how to build a sustain=
able and defensible business around its open source tools (right now most o=
f its revenue actually comes from renting out GPU capacity); Databricks=E2=
=80=99 original Spark-based business, meanwhile, is increasingly commoditiz=
ed, but undergirded by a well-developed sales organization with a moat base=
d on the inherent stickiness of data noted above. Going forward it is easy =
to envision MosaicML driving customer acquisition for Databricks=E2=80=99 s=
alesforce, and that those customers don=E2=80=99t go anywhere because data =
rarely moves.

Or maybe it=E2=80=99s all hype! I suspect, though, that picks-and-shovels-a=
s-a-service-with-data-as-a-moat (PaSaaSwDaaM) is going to be a popular mode=
l going forward.

